The paper discusses the performance limitations of batteries in autonomous robots, specifically in the context of an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) inspection mission on a wind farm. The paper proposes integrating battery prognostics and health management (PHM) with formal verification of autonomous robots. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) and Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the probabilistic model checking in PRISM, which falls under the Embedded Systems (cs.ET) sub-category. The paper also mentions existing formal verification studies of autonomous robots, which suggests that the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category may also be relevant. Finally, the paper discusses potential solutions to integrate battery PHM with formal verification, which suggests that the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category may also be relevant.
